'''Thirteenth grade''' or '''grade thirteen''' is the final year of [[secondary school]] in some jurisdictions. In some locales it is compulsory, while it is optional in others.

==Canada==
{{main|Ontario Academic Credit}}
The Ontario Academic Credit (OAC) ({{lang-fr|Cours préuniversitaire de l'Ontario}} or CPO) was a fifth year of secondary school education designed for students preparing for [[post-secondary education]] that existed in the province of [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. The OAC curriculum was codified by the Ontario Ministry of Education in ''Ontario Schools:&nbsp;Intermediate and Senior'' (OS:IS) and its revisions. The Ontario education system had five years of secondary education, the fifth year known as "grade 13" from 1921 to 1988. Then, grade 13 was replaced in 1983 by the OAC for students starting high school ([[grade 9]]). The OAC continued to act as a fifth year of secondary education until it was phased out in 2003.<ref name=vicl>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/details/ERIC_EJ907035|title=Pathways to university: The "Victory Lap" Phenomenon in Ontario/journal=Canadian Journal of Educational Administration and Policy|last1=Brady|first1=Patrick|last2=Allingham|first2=Philip|issue=113|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>

==United States==
Most jurisdictions in America require or offer only twelfth grade as the final year of secondary school. Some school districts in [[Oregon]] offer a thirteenth grade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/education/2014/10/high_schools_offer_a_fifth_year_of_high_school_13th_grade_is_a_great_idea.html|title=Welcome to 13th Grade!|last=Schuman|first=Rebecca|date=2014-10-22|work=Slate|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2014/10/five-year_high_schools_increas.html|title=Five-year high schools increasingly common, 'a creative disruption,' and soon to show improved graduation rates|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2014/02/a_fifth_year_in_high_school_ho.html|title=A fifth year in high school: How it works to get students a free year of college|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2014/10/oregon_to_revise_definition_of.html|title=Oregon to revise definition of high school 'graduate'|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/blogs/high-school-notes/2015/05/04/13th-grade-offers-some-teens-an-easier-transition-to-college|title=13th Grade Offers Some Teens an Easier Transition to College|last=Pannoni|first=Alexandra|date=May 4, 2015|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> In [[North Carolina]], early college high schools may provide 5 years, providing a grade 13.<ref name=":0" />

